00:00:25,960 --> 00:00:28,628
narrator: compression and extension springs...    

6
00:00:28,630 --> 00:00:32,097
♪          

7
00:00:32,099 --> 00:00:34,032
...micro drill bits...     

8
00:00:34,034 --> 00:00:38,504
♪          

9
00:00:38,506 --> 00:00:39,705
...skiffs...          

10
00:00:39,707 --> 00:00:43,643
♪          

11
00:00:43,645 --> 00:00:46,378
...and painted glass backsplashes.         

12
00:00:46,380 --> 00:00:51,918
♪          

13
00:00:53,988 --> 00:00:56,922
coiled wire springs are designed
to change shape        

14
00:00:56,924 --> 00:00:59,391
when weight is added or removed.          

15
00:00:59,393 --> 00:01:01,727
some coils, such as compression springs,  

16
00:01:01,729 --> 00:01:04,063
are made to keep components apart.     

17
00:01:04,065 --> 00:01:06,866
other types of coils, like extension springs,    

18
00:01:06,868 --> 00:01:10,937
hold things together while the spring expands and contracts. 

19
00:01:12,407 --> 00:01:14,540
♪          

20
00:01:14,542 --> 00:01:17,143
when a load is applied to a compression spring,    

21
00:01:17,145 --> 00:01:21,447
it contracts, while an extension
spring expands when pulled.  

22
00:01:23,484 --> 00:01:25,284
compression and extension springs     

23
00:01:25,286 --> 00:01:27,552
are made from steel wire.   

24
00:01:27,554 --> 00:01:30,489
the diameter and qualities of the wire varies,      

25
00:01:30,491 --> 00:01:33,558
depending on the use of the spring.         

26
00:01:33,560 --> 00:01:37,029
spooled onto a reel, the wire uncoils,       

27
00:01:37,031 --> 00:01:40,766
pulled by rollers,       
which lead to a forming machine.

28
00:01:40,768 --> 00:01:44,437
guide rollers steer the wire, as does this aperture.     

29
00:01:46,841 --> 00:01:48,974
multiple feed rollers push the wire         

30
00:01:48,976 --> 00:01:52,711
towards computerized forming tools.         

31
00:01:52,713 --> 00:01:56,048
the rollers pause, while the tools do their work, 

32
00:01:56,050 --> 00:02:00,586
and then resume to supply wire for the next spring.      

33
00:02:00,588 --> 00:02:04,390
meanwhile, other rollers push the wire around a mandrel,

34
00:02:04,392 --> 00:02:07,460
where it's coiled into an extension spring.   

35
00:02:07,462 --> 00:02:09,928
a side-arm controls the diameter,         

36
00:02:09,930 --> 00:02:13,466
while another tool cuts it to length.       

37
00:02:13,468 --> 00:02:17,002
the forming process has caused internal stresses. 

38
00:02:17,004 --> 00:02:22,608
to remove those stresses, the springs are heat-treated. 

39
00:02:22,610 --> 00:02:24,810
as the springs move out of the oven,        

40
00:02:24,812 --> 00:02:27,146
they travel through a cooling chamber.       

41
00:02:27,148 --> 00:02:29,148
the heating and controlled cooling            

42
00:02:29,150 --> 00:02:31,283
improves the physical properties,    

43
00:02:31,285 --> 00:02:35,354
allowing the springs to withstand repeated compression.

44
00:02:35,356 --> 00:02:37,622
with internal stresses relieved,

45
00:02:37,624 --> 00:02:42,161
it's time to work on the outer surface of the steel springs. 

46
00:02:42,163 --> 00:02:44,963
a rack conveyer dips extension springs       

47
00:02:44,965 --> 00:02:47,299
into a vat of water-based paint.

48
00:02:49,437 --> 00:02:52,171
the paint seeps into the crevices of the coils,   

49
00:02:52,173 --> 00:02:54,439
providing even paint coverage. 

50
00:02:54,441 --> 00:02:57,843
♪          

51
00:02:57,845 --> 00:03:00,846
then the rack conveyer takes the painted springs      

52
00:03:00,848 --> 00:03:03,515
on a ten-minute loop through an oven.        

53
00:03:03,517 --> 00:03:06,318
this step bakes the paint onto the steel,        

54
00:03:06,320 --> 00:03:09,422
providing a corrosion-resistant
finish.            

55
00:03:09,424 --> 00:03:14,259
this is what the springs look like before and after painting.

56
00:03:14,261 --> 00:03:17,596
these truck suspension springs are made differently.     

57
00:03:17,598 --> 00:03:21,200
♪          

58
00:03:21,202 --> 00:03:24,770
a machinist heats the end of a steel rod in a furnace,  

59
00:03:24,772 --> 00:03:28,207
inserting it between forming tools to taper it.   

60
00:03:28,209 --> 00:03:32,078
this taper will allow the   
completed spring to sit upright.

61
00:03:34,348 --> 00:03:39,719
next, the entire rod goes into a 1,796-degree furnace.    

62
00:03:41,355 --> 00:03:44,022
once the rod in red-hot and malleable,         

63
00:03:44,024 --> 00:03:45,424
it exits the furnace      

64
00:03:45,426 --> 00:03:48,694
and is transferred to the forming mandrel.    

65
00:03:48,696 --> 00:03:52,498
the mandrel spins to wind the soft, steel wire,     

66
00:03:52,500 --> 00:03:56,102
transforming the straight steel rod into a spring.    

67
00:03:56,104 --> 00:03:59,238
♪          

68
00:03:59,240 --> 00:04:04,109
the spring is placed in a bucket
and lifted to an oil bath.   

69
00:04:04,111 --> 00:04:06,979
the bath quenches and hardens the steel.           

70
00:04:06,981 --> 00:04:10,316
♪          

71
00:04:10,318 --> 00:04:13,052
then the spring travels through a furnace.       

72
00:04:13,054 --> 00:04:15,921
the heat burns off quenching oil residue.     

73
00:04:18,525 --> 00:04:21,260
a technician inserts the compression springs    

74
00:04:21,262 --> 00:04:22,928
in a revolving fixture,    

75
00:04:22,930 --> 00:04:27,132
allowing the ends of the springs
to extend outward.       

76
00:04:27,134 --> 00:04:30,869
as the fixture revolves, grinding wheels remove material

77
00:04:30,871 --> 00:04:33,471
to flatten the exposed ends.  

78
00:04:33,473 --> 00:04:36,274
this flattened profile is another way to ensure    

79
00:04:36,276 --> 00:04:38,511
that the springs will sit upright.       

80
00:04:40,481 --> 00:04:41,680
once complete,         

81
00:04:41,682 --> 00:04:44,282
the technician measures the height of the spring    

82
00:04:44,284 --> 00:04:46,552
to confirm that the correct amount of material 

83
00:04:46,554 --> 00:04:49,354
has been ground off.      

84
00:04:49,356 --> 00:04:52,258
the grinding has made a substantial difference.   

85
00:04:55,229 --> 00:04:58,430
the next machine removes surface flaws.         

86
00:04:58,432 --> 00:05:02,034
an operator places the spring inside the machine.      

87
00:05:04,105 --> 00:05:05,770
as the spring spins,      

88
00:05:05,772 --> 00:05:09,942
a fine, abrasive steel shot sands away imperfections.   

89
00:05:12,045 --> 00:05:14,580
you can see the difference this step makes in the spring 

90
00:05:14,582 --> 00:05:15,714
on the right.         

91
00:05:18,186 --> 00:05:22,655
the exposure to heat has made the steel wire more flexible. 

92
00:05:22,657 --> 00:05:25,591
a technician places the wire in a press machine       

93
00:05:25,593 --> 00:05:27,526
and sets the compression and height.          

94
00:05:29,330 --> 00:05:31,397
the press squeezes the coils  

95
00:05:31,399 --> 00:05:34,500
until the desired amount of compression is achieved.  

96
00:05:36,204 --> 00:05:38,270
after the spring has been painted,       

97
00:05:38,272 --> 00:05:40,405
the company name and model information     

98
00:05:40,407 --> 00:05:44,109
is stamped onto the springs.  

99
00:05:44,111 --> 00:05:46,878
it takes two hours to make a spring,       

100
00:05:46,880 --> 00:05:50,349
and now it's finally ready for some flex time.      

101
00:05:50,351 --> 00:05:53,185
♪          

102
00:06:00,228 --> 00:06:06,565
♪          

103
00:06:06,567 --> 00:06:09,568
narrator: thousands of years ago, our earliest ancestors  

104
00:06:09,570 --> 00:06:11,637
might have picked up a pointed rock         

105
00:06:11,639 --> 00:06:14,573
and spun it between their hands
to bore a hole         

106
00:06:14,575 --> 00:06:16,976
in something they wanted to modify.     

107
00:06:16,978 --> 00:06:20,913
today, you can buy drill bits in all shapes and sizes.    

108
00:06:25,920 --> 00:06:29,054
drill bits are often associated
with carpentry,        

109
00:06:29,056 --> 00:06:31,590
but from electronics to surgery tooling,      

110
00:06:31,592 --> 00:06:33,058
there are all kinds of fields 

111
00:06:33,060 --> 00:06:38,129
that require ultra-thin, high-performance drill bits.  

112
00:06:38,131 --> 00:06:40,332
the production process begins with lengths          

113
00:06:40,334 --> 00:06:43,669
of 100% carbide called blanks.         

114
00:06:43,671 --> 00:06:47,673
♪          

115
00:06:47,675 --> 00:06:48,941
a diamond grinding wheel    

116
00:06:48,943 --> 00:06:52,011
lubricated with a specialized cutting liquid         

117
00:06:52,013 --> 00:06:55,814
is applied to a chamfered edge on one tip of the blank.    

118
00:06:58,486 --> 00:07:00,552
this step removes the rough edges left      

119
00:07:00,554 --> 00:07:02,955
when the blanks were cut down to size.     

120
00:07:02,957 --> 00:07:06,425
♪          

121
00:07:06,427 --> 00:07:12,230
a vibrating device organizes the
blanks inside a rotating bowl. 

122
00:07:12,232 --> 00:07:15,834
the vibrating action shifts the blanks into single file  

123
00:07:15,836 --> 00:07:18,871
so they can proceed one-by-one to the next step.  

124
00:07:20,975 --> 00:07:24,442
this machine is called a centerless grinder.     

125
00:07:24,444 --> 00:07:27,645
the blanks move between two rotating drums,      

126
00:07:27,647 --> 00:07:30,782
which grinds them down to a specified length.     

127
00:07:30,784 --> 00:07:35,520
♪          

128
00:07:35,522 --> 00:07:37,522
the blanks pour out of the machine         

129
00:07:37,524 --> 00:07:40,192
immersed in the lubricating fluid.       

130
00:07:40,194 --> 00:07:42,928
an operator selects one and places it         

131
00:07:42,930 --> 00:07:45,330
in a quality control gauge to check            

132
00:07:45,332 --> 00:07:48,801
that it meets the manufacturer's
required tolerances.      

133
00:07:48,803 --> 00:07:54,473
♪          

134
00:07:54,475 --> 00:07:57,643
the blanks now enter a cnc rollomatic.       

135
00:07:59,613 --> 00:08:03,749
an operator sets up the tool and programs its work process. 

136
00:08:06,086 --> 00:08:09,421
a robotic auto-feeder picks up the blanks one-by-one     

137
00:08:09,423 --> 00:08:11,323
from a specialized palette.  

138
00:08:13,427 --> 00:08:16,094
the robotic arms places each blank carefully      

139
00:08:16,096 --> 00:08:19,765
and precisely in a waiting chuck, or collar, 

140
00:08:19,767 --> 00:08:22,067
and then moves them back into position.      

141
00:08:24,505 --> 00:08:28,374
the tool moves forward, holding
the blank perfectly still   

142
00:08:28,376 --> 00:08:30,542
as a pair of wheels close in. 

143
00:08:32,312 --> 00:08:34,913
liquid coolant pours over the blank         

144
00:08:34,915 --> 00:08:37,116
as the wheels precision pinch-grind          

145
00:08:37,118 --> 00:08:38,783
the tip of the blank,     

146
00:08:38,785 --> 00:08:41,920
grinding it down to about 1/10 of a millimeter --    

147
00:08:41,922 --> 00:08:43,988
the width of a human hair.   

148
00:08:43,990 --> 00:08:46,191
it's a delicate process.    

149
00:08:46,193 --> 00:08:49,528
the rollomatic produces 48 pieces per hour.      

150
00:08:52,066 --> 00:08:58,336
next, a technician places small
sheets of plastic foil in a jig.

151
00:08:58,338 --> 00:09:00,205
the foil is shim stock,    

152
00:09:00,207 --> 00:09:03,008
color-coded according to its thickness.  

153
00:09:03,010 --> 00:09:06,945
the jig raises the metal support
to a specified height.     

154
00:09:06,947 --> 00:09:09,548
when the blank advances over the support,       

155
00:09:09,550 --> 00:09:11,483
a mark left in the blue ink determines         

156
00:09:11,485 --> 00:09:13,552
whether the metal blank is centered.          

157
00:09:15,756 --> 00:09:19,224
once complete, a technician uses
a magnifying tool       

158
00:09:19,226 --> 00:09:21,693
to fine-tune the placement of the blank   

159
00:09:21,695 --> 00:09:24,696
and ensure that it's perfectly centered.    

160
00:09:24,698 --> 00:09:28,200
this process can take four to five hours.         

161
00:09:30,237 --> 00:09:33,839
the blank is finally ready for the crucial fluting process  

162
00:09:33,841 --> 00:09:37,376
that will transform it from a cylindrical length of carbide

163
00:09:37,378 --> 00:09:41,246
with a narrow tip into a micro drill bit.    

164
00:09:41,248 --> 00:09:43,315
after hours of preparation,  

165
00:09:43,317 --> 00:09:46,785
this operation takes just a few seconds.      

166
00:09:46,787 --> 00:09:49,188
an industrial grinding diamond wheel         

167
00:09:49,190 --> 00:09:53,125
has sliced a microscopic groove
at a precise angle.      

168
00:09:53,127 --> 00:09:56,394
the technician inserts the bit,
sharp-end first,        

169
00:09:56,396 --> 00:09:59,264
into a precision machining device.       

170
00:09:59,266 --> 00:10:01,666
a steel bushing with a brass insert      

171
00:10:01,668 --> 00:10:04,002
holds the tip of the bit in place            

172
00:10:04,004 --> 00:10:07,039
as a cutting wheel slices an angled point.        

173
00:10:07,041 --> 00:10:10,809
♪          

174
00:10:10,811 --> 00:10:14,213
it's impossible to see the difference between a bit before

175
00:10:14,215 --> 00:10:16,681
and after fluting.       

176
00:10:16,683 --> 00:10:19,817
using a magnifying device, the technician conducts    

177
00:10:19,819 --> 00:10:22,554
a quality control check of the bit.       

178
00:10:22,556 --> 00:10:25,624
as the screen reveals the finely-cut flute,     

179
00:10:25,626 --> 00:10:28,560
the technician ensures the tool's parameters meet   

180
00:10:28,562 --> 00:10:30,895
manufacturing standards.    

181
00:10:30,897 --> 00:10:34,299
once such parameter has to do with the shape of the flute,  

182
00:10:34,301 --> 00:10:36,234
which has a forward taper.   

183
00:10:36,236 --> 00:10:38,970
this means the flue groove becomes shallower       

184
00:10:38,972 --> 00:10:43,175
from tip to base at a very precise angle.     

185
00:10:43,177 --> 00:10:46,644
this feature simultaneously strengthens the tool      

186
00:10:46,646 --> 00:10:51,250
while increasing the chip flow along the groove.       

187
00:10:51,252 --> 00:10:54,052
although carbide is incredibly strong,     

188
00:10:54,054 --> 00:10:56,488
when it's milled to the thickness of a human hair, 

189
00:10:56,490 --> 00:10:58,056
it becomes fragile.      

190
00:10:58,058 --> 00:10:59,391
needless to say,        

191
00:10:59,393 --> 00:11:02,628
careful packaging is extremely important.    

192
00:11:10,070 --> 00:11:15,073
♪          

193
00:11:15,075 --> 00:11:17,476
narrator: a skiff is a lightweight motorboat    

194
00:11:17,478 --> 00:11:20,078
designed for use on shallow water.       

195
00:11:20,080 --> 00:11:23,081
unlike most boats that have a v-shaped hull,        

196
00:11:23,083 --> 00:11:25,684
a skiff's hull is relatively flat,      

197
00:11:25,686 --> 00:11:28,387
allowing it to sit high above the water.     

198
00:11:35,162 --> 00:11:38,096
this type of boat is known as a poling skiff.       

199
00:11:38,098 --> 00:11:41,366
it's designed with a platform set over the engine,      

200
00:11:41,368 --> 00:11:44,369
which provides fishermen a ledge
to stand on          

201
00:11:44,371 --> 00:11:48,040
while moving the boat along with a pole.       

202
00:11:48,042 --> 00:11:50,509
a technician cleans the hull mold         

203
00:11:50,511 --> 00:11:52,710
and coats it with a release agent,        

204
00:11:52,712 --> 00:11:55,447
then sprays on a gel coating. 

205
00:11:55,449 --> 00:12:00,052
the gel coating forms the glossy
outer layer of the boat.    

206
00:12:00,054 --> 00:12:03,788
then the technician measures the
gel coat layer with a mill gauge

207
00:12:03,790 --> 00:12:06,058
and leaves it to harden for about an hour.       

208
00:12:08,262 --> 00:12:11,863
computer-guided machines cut pieces for the hull, deck, 

209
00:12:11,865 --> 00:12:15,067
and cockpit floor       
from four different materials --

210
00:12:15,069 --> 00:12:19,805
woven fiberglass mat, rigid pvc sheet-foam, kevlar --

211
00:12:19,807 --> 00:12:22,608
a high-strength, heat-resistant
synthetic fabric --      

212
00:12:22,610 --> 00:12:27,145
and stiffer kevlar reinforced with carbon fiber. 

213
00:12:27,147 --> 00:12:30,081
chopped fiberglass saturated with resin           

214
00:12:30,083 --> 00:12:33,218
is applied onto the gel coat. 

215
00:12:33,220 --> 00:12:36,088
with spray-glue, a technician adheres a layer        

216
00:12:36,090 --> 00:12:39,957
of carbon kevlar, fiberglass, foam,       

217
00:12:39,959 --> 00:12:43,027
and a second layer of kevlar to the base.     

218
00:12:43,029 --> 00:12:46,565
these layered materials create a mold for the boat's deck   

219
00:12:46,567 --> 00:12:48,567
and cockpit floor.       

220
00:12:48,569 --> 00:12:51,436
the flat squares are aluminum-retention plates,   

221
00:12:51,438 --> 00:12:54,306
where components will be screwed down.     

222
00:12:54,308 --> 00:12:56,908
raised squares are where openings will be cut out    

223
00:12:56,910 --> 00:12:59,711
for storage compartments.   

224
00:12:59,713 --> 00:13:02,848
each mold is bagged and connected with hoses    

225
00:13:02,850 --> 00:13:05,384
to a vacuum-infusion system.  

226
00:13:05,386 --> 00:13:09,855
the vacuum compresses the layers
to 2/3 their original thickness,

227
00:13:09,857 --> 00:13:12,324
then the system draws a specialized resin      

228
00:13:12,326 --> 00:13:13,692
through the materials,     

229
00:13:13,694 --> 00:13:16,261
which will bond them into a single unit.      

230
00:13:16,263 --> 00:13:18,863
the system removes all excess resin        

231
00:13:18,865 --> 00:13:21,399
so that the ratio of resin to materials          

232
00:13:21,401 --> 00:13:24,202
creates maximum strength with minimal weight.      

233
00:13:26,340 --> 00:13:29,674
next, another technician assembles the boat's wiring  

234
00:13:29,676 --> 00:13:32,477
into a unit known as a wiring harness.      

235
00:13:32,479 --> 00:13:35,814
he winds the individual wires around a schematic       

236
00:13:35,816 --> 00:13:38,883
that's custom-designed for this specific boat.    

237
00:13:38,885 --> 00:13:41,219
he attaches connectors on the ends          

238
00:13:41,221 --> 00:13:43,688
that fit into water-tight plugs.

239
00:13:43,690 --> 00:13:48,493
every wire is labeled for easy identification.    

240
00:13:48,495 --> 00:13:50,762
once the resin has fully cured,

241
00:13:50,764 --> 00:13:54,899
the plastic vacuum bag is removed from each mold.   

242
00:13:54,901 --> 00:13:57,836
a technician knocks wedges under the flange that formed  

243
00:13:57,838 --> 00:14:01,840
around the perimeter,     
and thanks to the release agent,

244
00:14:01,842 --> 00:14:05,777
a team can easily lift the flange out of the mold.  

245
00:14:05,779 --> 00:14:07,446
the flange is trimmed,     

246
00:14:07,448 --> 00:14:10,115
and the openings are cut with a diamond saw,      

247
00:14:10,117 --> 00:14:13,318
which leaves clean, straight edges.        

248
00:14:13,320 --> 00:14:16,455
next, a team begins assembling the boat.      

249
00:14:16,457 --> 00:14:19,057
first, they apply adhesive to the hull          

250
00:14:19,059 --> 00:14:22,461
to prepare the cockpit floor for attachment.        

251
00:14:22,463 --> 00:14:26,798
once the cockpit's in place, white pvc tubes are installed 

252
00:14:26,800 --> 00:14:29,400
for storing fishing rods under the deck.        

253
00:14:29,402 --> 00:14:32,737
then the wiring harness is installed.         

254
00:14:32,739 --> 00:14:35,940
the aluminum fuel tank is mounted in the bow.     

255
00:14:35,942 --> 00:14:40,412
these components are made of strong, lightweight materials. 

256
00:14:40,414 --> 00:14:43,949
a technician places screws into
the metal retention plates   

257
00:14:43,951 --> 00:14:46,684
that were molded into the structure.      

258
00:14:46,686 --> 00:14:50,756
next, the wiring harness    
is attached to water-tight plugs

259
00:14:50,758 --> 00:14:54,091
connected to the        
electrically-powered components.

260
00:14:54,093 --> 00:14:55,827
after installing plumbing lines

261
00:14:55,829 --> 00:14:58,563
for the aerated live bait compartment,     

262
00:14:58,565 --> 00:15:02,700
team members glue the deck to the hull.     

263
00:15:02,702 --> 00:15:06,037
the lids are installed for the deck openings.     

264
00:15:06,039 --> 00:15:08,507
this one covers the forward storage compartment      

265
00:15:08,509 --> 00:15:12,377
containing the fuel tank and the tubes for the fishing rods.

266
00:15:12,379 --> 00:15:16,914
♪          

267
00:15:16,916 --> 00:15:19,651
next, the console helm is assembled,         

268
00:15:19,653 --> 00:15:23,721
which is the nautical equivalent
of a vehicle dashboard.    

269
00:15:23,723 --> 00:15:27,459
onto the helm, a technician installs the steering wheel,  

270
00:15:27,461 --> 00:15:28,926
the engine gauge,       

271
00:15:28,928 --> 00:15:30,728
the panel containing the ignition          

272
00:15:30,730 --> 00:15:33,398
and switches for electrical components,   

273
00:15:33,400 --> 00:15:35,934
and the throttle, which controls speed.     

274
00:15:38,739 --> 00:15:41,473
then, two technicians bolt the outboard motor       

275
00:15:41,475 --> 00:15:44,676
onto the engine mount at the stern.         

276
00:15:44,678 --> 00:15:47,011
while this skiff is built with a square stern      

277
00:15:47,013 --> 00:15:50,749
and pointed bow, its sides are flat.      

278
00:15:50,751 --> 00:15:54,019
this enables the boat to move quietly through the water.   

279
00:15:56,356 --> 00:16:00,158
next, technicians mount the  
poling platform over the engine,

280
00:16:00,160 --> 00:16:02,894
securing it with glue and screws.          

281
00:16:02,896 --> 00:16:07,899
♪          

282
00:16:07,901 --> 00:16:11,236
finally, a technician installs the finishing touches,

283
00:16:11,238 --> 00:16:13,705
and the skiff is ready for launch.      

284
00:16:13,707 --> 00:16:16,374
due to its low profile and light weight,       

285
00:16:16,376 --> 00:16:20,111
this boat can operate in just mere inches of water. 

286
00:16:27,721 --> 00:16:33,325
♪          

287
00:16:33,327 --> 00:16:36,928
narrator: painted glass is an 
un-traditional backsplash choice

288
00:16:36,930 --> 00:16:39,864
specifically designed to look minimalistic.     

289
00:16:39,866 --> 00:16:42,733
due to fewer grout lines, these painted panels      

290
00:16:42,735 --> 00:16:46,737
are also easier to clean so that when grease splatters, 

291
00:16:46,739 --> 00:16:49,574
the backsplash can be wiped down quickly.      

292
00:16:52,279 --> 00:16:53,745
♪          

293
00:16:53,747 --> 00:16:55,814
these panels are painted on the back          

294
00:16:55,816 --> 00:16:59,017
so the neutral color shows through the front side. 

295
00:16:59,019 --> 00:17:01,086
since glass is reflective,   

296
00:17:01,088 --> 00:17:03,821
this backsplash brings both subtle color       

297
00:17:03,823 --> 00:17:06,691
and light into the kitchen.  

298
00:17:06,693 --> 00:17:10,161
production starts with an automated loading system.  

299
00:17:10,163 --> 00:17:12,230
suctioning grippers transfer the glass       

300
00:17:12,232 --> 00:17:14,165
to the rails of a conveyer.  

301
00:17:14,167 --> 00:17:16,500
♪          

302
00:17:16,502 --> 00:17:18,637
this is low-iron glass,    

303
00:17:18,639 --> 00:17:21,573
a kind of glass with a very high clarity.   

304
00:17:21,575 --> 00:17:23,841
once color is applied to the back,          

305
00:17:23,843 --> 00:17:26,444
the color will appear more clearly on the front   

306
00:17:26,446 --> 00:17:28,779
than regular glass.      

307
00:17:28,781 --> 00:17:32,249
for easy identification, a computerized system     

308
00:17:32,251 --> 00:17:35,086
applies labels to each of the parts to be cut.

309
00:17:36,990 --> 00:17:40,058
a diamond cutting tool scores the glass,       

310
00:17:40,060 --> 00:17:43,394
mapping out backsplash panels and smaller pieces       

311
00:17:43,396 --> 00:17:45,497
to be used for showroom samples.     

312
00:17:47,734 --> 00:17:51,803
once complete, rollers move the
glass sheet to the next station.

313
00:17:51,805 --> 00:17:56,273
♪          

314
00:17:56,275 --> 00:17:59,944
two technicians snap the glass along the score lines.     

315
00:17:59,946 --> 00:18:05,082
♪          

316
00:18:05,084 --> 00:18:07,485
this snapping action creates clean cuts,      

317
00:18:07,487 --> 00:18:09,788
preventing the glass from shattering.        

318
00:18:12,292 --> 00:18:15,893
the snap action doesn't work for cuts within the panel.   

319
00:18:15,895 --> 00:18:20,031
instead, a highly pressurized 
water jet mixed with garnet grit

320
00:18:20,033 --> 00:18:22,233
cuts through the glass.    

321
00:18:22,235 --> 00:18:25,703
the cutting device makes holes for electrical switch plates  

322
00:18:25,705 --> 00:18:28,306
and for mounting hardware.   

323
00:18:28,308 --> 00:18:29,707
with the cutting done,     

324
00:18:29,709 --> 00:18:32,177
a technician rinses the residual grit.       

325
00:18:34,313 --> 00:18:36,047
the sharp edges are profiled  

326
00:18:36,049 --> 00:18:38,849
so the glass will be safer to handle.           

327
00:18:38,851 --> 00:18:41,052
as this display model demonstrates,         

328
00:18:41,054 --> 00:18:44,055
there are several choices.   

329
00:18:44,057 --> 00:18:47,658
next, an operator loads the glass backsplash      

330
00:18:47,660 --> 00:18:49,327
into a slotted conveyer,    

331
00:18:49,329 --> 00:18:52,263
which transfers it to the edging machine.     

332
00:18:52,265 --> 00:18:53,931
underneath the edging machine, 

333
00:18:53,933 --> 00:18:57,002
there are a series of grinding and buffing wheels.      

334
00:18:57,004 --> 00:18:59,604
as the glass travels over the wheels,          

335
00:18:59,606 --> 00:19:01,940
the edge of the glass will transform.        

336
00:19:03,677 --> 00:19:07,078
once the machine is activated, the wheels spin,        

337
00:19:07,080 --> 00:19:10,281
while lubricant flows over the glass.     

338
00:19:10,283 --> 00:19:13,551
the wheels profile and buff the edge of the glass     

339
00:19:13,553 --> 00:19:16,087
that will be the top of the backsplash.       

340
00:19:18,558 --> 00:19:21,559
next, the operator examines the edge to confirm      

341
00:19:21,561 --> 00:19:23,094
that it's been contoured    

342
00:19:23,096 --> 00:19:25,363
and that there aren't any imperfections.       

343
00:19:27,434 --> 00:19:30,702
apart from making the glass safer to handle,        

344
00:19:30,704 --> 00:19:33,371
the profiled edge will reduce the possibility        

345
00:19:33,373 --> 00:19:36,507
of chipping and breakage.   

346
00:19:36,509 --> 00:19:37,775
at the next station,      

347
00:19:37,777 --> 00:19:41,846
spinning brushes with soft bristles scrub the panel.   

348
00:19:44,384 --> 00:19:47,318
the process removes any dust or polishing grit       

349
00:19:47,320 --> 00:19:50,455
to prepare it for the next steps.      

350
00:19:50,457 --> 00:19:52,390
once out of the washing machine,

351
00:19:52,392 --> 00:19:58,730
the glass backsplash travels through a 1,299-degree oven.  

352
00:19:58,732 --> 00:20:01,532
the intense heat followed by a quick cooling       

353
00:20:01,534 --> 00:20:04,402
tempers the glass to make it heat resistant.   

354
00:20:06,606 --> 00:20:10,275
roller conveyers transfer the glass to the painting station. 

355
00:20:10,277 --> 00:20:13,411
♪          

356
00:20:13,413 --> 00:20:16,214
a technician mixes the acrylic paint.       

357
00:20:16,216 --> 00:20:19,216
since paint doesn't stick to glass on its own,      

358
00:20:19,218 --> 00:20:21,686
a special adhesion-promoting chemical  

359
00:20:21,688 --> 00:20:23,922
is added to the mixture.    

360
00:20:23,924 --> 00:20:27,292
the technician mixes the colorants into the white base 

361
00:20:27,294 --> 00:20:29,894
according to the formula.   

362
00:20:29,896 --> 00:20:32,363
specific amounts of red and yellow paint        

363
00:20:32,365 --> 00:20:34,565
produce a brilliant orange hue.

364
00:20:34,567 --> 00:20:40,038
♪          

365
00:20:40,040 --> 00:20:42,306
next, sprayers apply the paint 

366
00:20:42,308 --> 00:20:44,708
evenly across the back of the panel          

367
00:20:44,710 --> 00:20:47,245
as the glass moves along a conveyer.       

368
00:20:47,247 --> 00:20:50,381
♪          

369
00:20:50,383 --> 00:20:53,318
then the backsplash enters an infrared oven        

370
00:20:53,320 --> 00:20:56,187
heated to 302 degrees fahrenheit.          

371
00:20:56,189 --> 00:20:59,257
♪          

372
00:20:59,259 --> 00:21:03,127
the painted glass bakes in   
the oven for about four minutes.

373
00:21:03,129 --> 00:21:06,464
♪          

374
00:21:06,466 --> 00:21:09,934
once heating is complete, a technician applies gray paint

375
00:21:09,936 --> 00:21:12,537
over the backside of the backsplash.       

376
00:21:12,539 --> 00:21:14,806
this coat won't affect the orange hue,        

377
00:21:14,808 --> 00:21:17,342
but it will protect the backsplash from damage   

378
00:21:17,344 --> 00:21:19,410
during transport and installation.       

379
00:21:21,481 --> 00:21:25,083
neutral-colored backsplashes make a more subtle statement, 

380
00:21:25,085 --> 00:21:26,884
while brightly-colored backsplashes          

381
00:21:26,886 --> 00:21:28,486
can make a kitchen pop.    

